Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the ex-prime minister's release, but the parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes at second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a deal with Russia that disadvantaged Ukraine over the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, the appeals court is obliged to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there have been doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Penal Code condemning the former prime minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
It required 226 votes to pass.
