Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner on the menu
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9% of the school population being overweight and 5% being obese.
Obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to current research.
It is again demonstrated the importance of the environment in which it grows for healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obese children eat, for example, at least twice as often as children from families with normal weight.
For dinner, more than 19 percent of obese people had had had fries the day before the test, which is linked to the "Obesity is not a coincidence" prevention program.
In families of overweight children there is no practice of sports, which is applicable to most families today, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 children from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of the "Obesity is not a coincidence" program, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
A proper diet and adequate family exercise are determining factors, which significantly reduce the number of overweight and even obese children.
"Only half of the children surveyed have said they have five meals a day according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, food, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet", says one of the survey results.
No breakfast but with dinner stuffed
Specialists warn that in healthy development, details are important, as well as counting, such as having a set time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of schoolchildren's families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
But the worst part was finding out that in 10% of households, there's no breakfast.
Breakfast, however, is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children, crazy fries are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet refreshments daily (70%).
Over 40% of children surveyed are normally active in sports, but between parents this figure is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make your own diet
The next phase of the study allowed the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years old, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far from ideal".
Her favorite foods include pasta, meat, and sweets
"The popularity of sweet drinks is especially alarming", warns the final report of the study.
The main food is the palm, the pasta, and the poultry.
Children almost always reject vegetables and fish and vegetables taste very low.
Changing to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of study participants, who completed the questionnaire after finishing the prevention programme 'Obesity is not a coincidence', a major change in favour of the principles of healthy eating was made in many cases", the study findings point out.
It is a matter of sweet refreshments, for example, where many children would start to prefer regular, running water.
Children would also choose poultrymeat and fish for their main meal more frequently in the questionnaire and restrict their consumption of sweet food and flour products.
The stylist must also be a good psychologist, say the professionals
In the introductory article, How stylists learn, I already complained a little that the initial lessons were already quite loaded.
