In Need for Speed: The Run, you compete all over America.
Reviews
A journey, in principle carefree, becomes complicated by a series of improper carelessness from a routine trip during the morning shift.
To some extent, expectations were met, but it is of no use if, in fact, nothing extraordinary was intended.
The new installment, which includes The Run, has raised high expectations even before its release.
It promised to give new air to the old Need for Speed racing saga and, following what was shown, appears as a game that should not end up being an action genre again.
We also wondered what the inserted scenes would look like, where the main character gets out of the car and walks on his own foot.
As is often the case in NFS series, the results do not vary much from what we expected.
There are races that can be considered acceptable, but in total computation points are lost due to absurd errors, which have been appearing in the series for years.
In fact, they cannot even be called errors, but rather the incomprehensible mischief of programmers.
The adventure starts off very well.
You're introduced to a story, the protagonist of which, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he's offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You're driving on the West Coast, in San Francisco, and your mission is to get to New York first.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race takes place on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
Thus, one does not have the remote feeling that the game always offers the same.
Some of the environments are even pleasing to the eye, although the technical level of the graphic is equivalent to that of previous installments of the series.
So it's nothing of the other world.
But a walk in the desert, the autumn landscape, or the high mountains covered in snow produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, races are occasionally diversified by an atypical element.
So, for example, in the desert you find a sandstorm that diminishes visibility.
But in the mountains, you have to be careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There's only a couple models, but that's enough.
For a moment, you try to outrun a required number of rivals (normal in a classic race), then you try to gain time (timed classic duel) and then a duel against a single opponent awaits you.
In the midst of all this, the police sometimes appear, which only makes things more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape from someone and you have to help him, always pressing the right button at the right time.
It's not complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are quite a few landscapes in the game than would be expected (specifically there are only three).
But the end result is positive, because this element doesn't get annoying and, in the context already mentioned, it's one of the elements that makes the game more interesting.
The driving pattern follows the footprints of previous episodes.
That means that today it is no longer a big deal, but it cannot be said to be bad.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you can look elsewhere.
But a race designed with plenty of action is quite suitable for this style of driving, although we can find something better among the competition games.
So far, everything is in order.
But problems arise after a while.
Unlike the correct driving models, the same thing no longer happens with collisions.
Games like this can't be expected to recreate complicated deformities and collisions, but in fact before a hit on any object, you can't predict how your car will react, so not everything is in order.
Typically, when you drive a very tight overhead or drive around a car with normal traffic, there are only slight bumps, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up running out of control.
Or it ends up completely destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, no big problems arise, but it can make you feel bad.
Reset is programmed in such a way that when you have an accident or you leave the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, only five resets are available in each race.
If you consume them all, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it's just a help in case something goes wrong, but it's not very reliable.
Sometimes resetting doesn't help, it just helps to learn the given memory stage.
A big disadvantage of the game is that the same events are repeated in different places.
For example, in some curves, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, you cannot take them.
Other times you find yourself somewhere "civil" vehicles always with the same configuration, whether you are first, fifth or arriving five minutes earlier or later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see two cars meeting in opposite directions, your opponent advances without problems, but when you arrive, you must either turn or brake.
It doesn't matter when you arrive, because it's programmed so that the "surprise" will always happen before your eyes.
The opponents also have one more advantage.
Throughout the game you will reach places where, regardless of the timing, you will always be outnumbered by the same opponent in the same place.
And this happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must arrive before you, at whatever cost.
When it goes in front of you, it makes it hard for you to see the cars coming in front of you, so at first you can make the car go away.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so apparent that it's sure to disappoint you right away.
And it's a shame, because while the model of travel is simple, the game is fun and action-packed, so it's often not possible to follow in detail what happens or where.
And it really doesn't matter, if the merit is to take the idea with fifty exclusive tracks or the qualifying in the race so that it doesn't dull the boredom, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to be careful of the gas stations on the side of the road, because that's where you have to change cars, although in the vast majority of cases you will have enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, American heavy cars for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain roads.
In addition to the main narrative thread there is also a parallel challenge thread, that is, there are races in specific places that you will know from the stories.
Here you'll get not only medals, but experience points for your profile, which serves both challenges and stories.
When the driver reaches the top level, several possibilities are opened up to him, starting with the car and ending with profiling funds.
At the same time, an online Autolog feature is connected, which compares your results with those of other players and makes other community features available.
One of the hardest things to understand is how the last race in history is done.
You drive to the subway tunnel (passage), where you run in the dark down the tracks (passage).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and, suddenly, the convoy of the subway arrives behind you and is taken ahead of you without further action.
In the newsroom we'll probably have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the game's programming no one thought even a little bit or whether the authors really take us for a panda of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the overall visual effects result in most pleasant, sometimes even superb, cases.
It is a pity that, in the most stressful moments, the quality of the image is reduced and sometimes seriously.
This is particularly true in accidents involving many participants, when continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
To please most youth groups, the soundtrack falls into the category of "everyone's father and mother", but one can assume that no one would buy the game just for their music.
The final feel of Need for Speed: The Run is quite confusing.
If the game avoided absolutely stupid mistakes, we would have trouble saying The Run is the best NFS game of recent years.
It gives the feeling that the game isn't over.
Fun is guaranteed, but get ready because mistakes will hit you in the eye with the force of airport reflectors.
The choirs at the University of Carolina will participate in the "Students of Terciopelo" concert.
The joint celebration of International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution as a musical experience will take place for the third time at the Festa Academica festival.
During the same, twenty choirs from secondary and university schools will be presented.
The festival revolves around two concerts on November 17.
"Carolina State University has a high participation rate in the festival".
Among the current choirs are the choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and the Faculty of Humanities, in the festival committee is the rector Václav Hampl", said the organization's head, Jakub Čaloun.
The summit of the entire festival is free admission for all audiences to the high school choirs concert, which will be held on March 17 at 14 hours in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme features the participation of Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička and his Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, the concert "Terticiopelo Students" will be held at the venues of the Municipal House in Vynohrady, where university choirs will participate, including the Carolina University choir.
The purpose of the Academic Festival is not only to celebrate the International Day of Students and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Terciopelo Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to promote collaborative creation among young people.
The main organiser is the Czech Coral Union in collaboration with the Jan Kepler High School Institute.
All the events were supported by Prague Mayor Bohuslav Svoboda and the rector of the University of Carolina, Václav Hampl.
The Festival will take place between 16 and 20 November between Prague and Pardubice.
The calendar offers, in addition to the celebration concerts, a whole series of musical events, improvised student shows and morning concerts.
The festival is open to all interested parties at www.festaacademica.cz
The EU Ambassador to the EU, Vicenová:
The Czechs have a reputation for being negative and Eurosceptic.
"The Lisbon Treaty has significantly affected the balance between individual institutions"
"I didn't expect a war without barracks".
"It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes a little, calms down and the new players get used to their new roles", Czech Ambassador to the EU Milena Vicenová began her lecture at the Faculty of Law with conviction.
How can we not take seriously his slogan "clear and open about Europe", which he said in the first part of his lecture, when he managed to describe each EU body and its relations with such precision and clarity, as would be the envy of many lecturers at the U.S. Law School.
Vicenová also weighed in on the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman van Rompuy:
"The first thing that comes up is the criticism, that if he's rude, a gray official, capable of taking on any role, but I have to say he left everyone baffled, because he takes on his roles perfectly".
"He is a man who knows how to listen to the members of the 27 states, communicate with them and has a very clear vision of where the EU should go".
The new position of Foreign and Security Policy representative is explained by the question: 'Who is this EU? What number can I call it?'
No one wants to ban Olomouc cheese
Vicenová has also taken care of the agenda for the European Council in the near future.
The Czech presidency two years ago was a success.
The Czechs dealt with the emerging economic crisis, resolved the gas crisis and organized a summit for the Eastern Association.
The fall of the government at the time was identified as a very negative aspect, which seriously affected the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU has many commitments at the moment.
In the words of the Ambassador: "a good uproar", not only the presidency, but also the financial crisis, which is being dealt with now.
On the other hand, the EU's seven-year budget has to be approved, because of the much more complicated economic situation.
If the budget is simpler and more effective, which sectors will be given priority, which countries will receive the most support and which will receive the least?
The Ambassador also recalled her main slogans, with which she arrived in Europe: "About Europe clearly".
"The truth is, I don't like ugly abbreviations, foreigners, or jargon that people don't understand".
"How can a citizen understand that in Brussels cucumbers are not really invented, curved or round cucumbers, bananas of various sizes or that nobody is going to ban Olomouc cheese from us?"
It also aims to make the most of the EU environment and bring more Czech citizens closer to the European institutions.
We are waiting for Europe of speeds
According to the ambassador, Czechs are known to be Eurosceptics and people perceive the negative rather than the positive.
It also deplored the low participation of Czechs in the European institutions.
The blame lies with a multitude of factors, such as the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational messages, but also the lack of support from the Czechs.
In addition to the success of the Czech presidency, he highlighted the strength and collaboration of the Visegrad Group.
"I believe that when a Polish and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak comes to me, a Frenchman next to me says, 'What, you guys from the Visegrad Group are staying?' and it looks like he's not making any fun of it".
In the future, the EU, according to Vicenová, is expected to face new, very tough budgetary policy rules for the Member States.
It is perceived as something very real of the concept of the two speeds, if not more, in Europe, than the new one of the "European Federation".
"We have countries in the Eurozone and countries outside the Eurozone".
"We have the Schengen area and we have the enhanced cooperation procedure".
"It was said for the first time that only countries that want to cooperate and those that don't, stay out".
"These procedures will be increasing and will strengthen the two-speed Europe", Vicenová hopes.
In this regard, he also highlighted the role of the Czech Republic and Herman van Rompuy in implementing the principle that all issues affecting the EU as a whole should be discussed among the Member States, not just among the Eurozone members.
Brand story:
IBM is entering its second century of existence
If anyone were looking for a term that would define IBM's strategy very precisely, the closest one would be "long term".
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet has already passed a hundred years since its founding.
The basis for this long-term character was laid by the firm's first head, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" became his seal, around which he will build the future giant's life (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully crafted corporate culture.
"For us, IBM implies a long-term thinking, a continuous movement toward the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to prosper even more in our second century", said during his anniversary, the current director of the company Samuel J. Palmisano.
A sophisticated system
Watson, already in the 1930s, was concerned with the care of his employees as the entrepreneur of Baťa in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American operators to enjoy paid vacation, insurance, fancy uniforms and a sophisticated pay system that rewarded the best inventors and sellers.
The same long-term sophistication holds IBM in the relationship with the customer.
From the very beginning, the company was able to discover talent (as one of the first companies in the world to eliminate any form of discrimination, it was easy to choose).
