IBM history: from the cheese cutter to spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, originally called Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a trademark used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous "fixing clock", which allows control of employees' entry and exit.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint signed up the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation upon which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to register boxes.
During the first four years Watson ran the company, revenues doubled by $9 million and the company's great expansion across the continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years as chief executive, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the standard of computers of the time, came to market as the IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which in turn acquired the consulting part of Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering complete advice and high-value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying for the last three years is the concept of a smarter planet, which means a smarter planet.
The aim is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned or circumstances have not been improved, for example in terms of transport and city management.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the 'Smart Commerce' platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
As early as 1932 it opened a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe to do so.
Today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague, and there is also a world-renowned research team here that works with voice recognition.
