How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorised state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of the time sold in most cases only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, afterwards the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered travel to the West at the time, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend the night like this, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still not all was won.
The so-called "promises of change" that were the condition for travel to the West, were not granted to "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs would acquire.
The way Czechs travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
The fact that Croatia, the current favourite destination, was not free to travel until 1989 is a great paradox, which we are no longer aware of today.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed for travel to neighbouring Western European countries, leading to a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechs, for a long time, did not seem tired of the Western excursions, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in tents in parks, since our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czechs at the time was taking food (confections, stews, etc.) with them to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it the average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in travel demand.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 onwards, to regularly prepare travel using charter connections, which brought down travel prices in comparison to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs were traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the United States, which made our travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened back in 2000, when, thanks to huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, and it went to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries have been launched every year.
The exotic countries are visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States removed visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time in their history, and for the first time in their history, they spent over 15 thousand Czech crowns per head on travel abroad, including on the stay-site.
The General Assembly convened to elect the President, who could end up at a standstill again.
For almost five months, Czech football has been without a president and it is likely that Ivan Hašek's successor as President of the Czech Football Federation (FAČR) will not be known even after the call of the next Extraordinary General Assembly to be held this Thursday in Nymburk.
In fact, there is still no agreement on the voting rules to follow.
Without them, you cannot even vote to choose between the three candidates.
