Walls have eyes: How researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a July massacre in Norway that left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time before his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - you just have to go to Facebook.
"We realized that it was not that difficult to reach them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report on European digital populism by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook's shroud of personal information is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic features with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been using it for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then ran ads to them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
By reaching out via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry about immigration.
However, in a way, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen".
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in "Likes", wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom, driving the number of academic papers with the site's name in the title to nearly 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you tried to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You'd have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access", says Bartlett.
"Facebook removes all that -- you go to them directly".
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunken feats on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of drinking problems than students who kept quiet about the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who posts too many status updates with his booze.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it", said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We've found a way to identify at-risk children who otherwise wouldn't be diagnosed".
Facebook is also constantly "picking" its own population for data.
The site's Data Team has compiled statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of voter turnout in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - longtime digital freedom advocates who argue that the site should make its large amount of data available to others for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study he conducted with public Facebook walls of students.
"As far as they were concerned, it was just between them and their friends".
Then there's the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know what part of the information on a user's profile and wall messages is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things", Selwyn says.
That's why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paper subject and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for getting into the real world and talking to real people", he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social -- and a lot of social stuff still happens offline".
