It was only after Jobs' death that a full copy was discovered on VHS in the director's garage.
This little re-edited archive footage is the basis of Steve Jobs' 68-minute, lost interview, which arrives at Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
To someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there's great silence between questions and answers -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for precision.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to move faster toward topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, there's something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read post-career reviews of Jobs, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, the eager dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I've always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done".
Nobody knows why they do what they do, in business nobody thinks things too deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs goes into detail about his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Confused by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was done in good faith, and then adjusted to a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine commercial costs in detail.
About the Pope joke:
Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" that he built himself with Steve Wozniak -- a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
There's been a lot written about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half dozen times and you were yelling through the public phone and coming back a minute later to the public phone from the next door", Jobs says with a laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world".
We didn't know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling on the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, while hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees".
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode-tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I'd get a ride to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Early in his career, as he was devoted to selling a handful of base plates, he was asked by a client if he could assemble the entire equipment.
Working with only 30 credit days, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to create a $300 mouse], and I got tired and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for 15 dollars and that was totally reliable.
About the big companies losing their strength:
Long before he led the Apple revival, Jobs predicted how many industry leaders would stumble upon his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, and what?"
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it's this kind of people who end up running businesses and the people in charge of the products are kicked out of the decision-making forum.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position is rotting because of people who don't have the notion of good products vs. bad products - the knowledge of the necessary craft.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took the defeat from the victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There's a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows".
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make -- some things you can't make that electrons do, glass does, robots do, factories do.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain -- these concepts -- adjust them all at once...
It all comes down to taste -- it comes down to trying to expose you to the best a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What made the Macintosh great in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
