How to detect a lie
A look at the latest headlines shows us just how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy swapping accusations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Penn State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weiner made a mockery of his denials quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to covering up an extramarital affair.
And again, no one who lived through it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
There are a lot of legends about school and college exam traps.
There have been cases where teachers have given the students their test answers in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find ourselves in?
On any given day, studies show they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Sure, a lot of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "locating lies", is an essential skill that we all must acquire, for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim, "I have you", cheating detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades from prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars do look into the eyes.
They don't always stutter, stutter, blush or get nervous.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or expose.
A trained lie detector can get to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation and timing.
I spent several years probing the scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-directed lies", while women tell more "other-directed lies" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they usually tell tend to be "big").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline".
It helps to provide benchmarks for measuring changes later.
Look at the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristics.
You better know if someone normally kicks their foot all the time so they don't make unfair accusations when they see their feet kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of misleading, verbal and nonverbal behavior.
Consider these behavioural groups as warning signs, not evidence of deception.
Cheating people can freeze their upper body trying to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, significantly change their posture or exhibit a "post-interview discharge" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators make it seem that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
It also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson got his foot in the door and used the past time while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
Cheating people can also use distant language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... as far as I... as I understand it".
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There's no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to detect deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding being victimized by the artists of the scam in their professional and personal lives.
