"What we are seeing is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation that was passed in congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars illicitly it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something", he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that there is also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state to seek work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of the difficulties of entering, and secondly because entering they already have many difficulties of finding work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise", he stated.
Informal
The analysis of the Sinaloense labour market is aggravated by the high level of informality that prevails among working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being quoting as a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informalism, the state's labor arrears are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of Sinaloese workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contracting of FDI
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment of the last 10 years is recorded, according to the Economy Secretariat from January to June of the state FDI amounted to 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded during the same period of the previous year.
The State Government's Economic Development Secretariat accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the context of economic contraction, the state government requested in July to the state congress the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, which would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2 billion 600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of debt in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés's government shows a lack of management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the various sectors, including the state government.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, failed to align the effort of everyone and above all the good march already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
Economic slowdown
Loredo López said events like the frosts of early this year halted the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including the freezes, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below expectations", he said.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he stated that it is necessary to prosecute the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated", he said.
I work to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better guides the Government's efforts.
"In general terms I would say that the Government has been striving to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term programme is developed", he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can only say that there is work done and I think the Government is aware that there is work to be done", he said.
