Court validates "analog apagón" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have put up against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogous apagon" from 2021 to 2015, by not gathering the eight votes needed to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital terrestrial television concrete.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for not reaching a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft judgment, drawn up by minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and law reserve.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and while admitting the demands, the minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions in it prepared for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers decided to dismiss the demand put forward by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering the discussion of the project, also in charge of the minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister-president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I also do not believe that if I did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector correspond to the Federal Executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the State rectorate.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, and it translates into better use of radio spectrum, improved signal quality and more channels.
The Commission's proposal for a directive on the protection of workers' rights and the protection of workers' rights in the Member States is a key step forward.
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic rectory of the State, encompassing a group of responsibilities that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, which in some way invades the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it is providing in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislature, he assured.
They analyze the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 percent, yet without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the total 6,74 acts.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to data thrown by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is just 27 percent, yet without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total acts.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As you will recall, Michoacán did not approve his Political Constitution nor his Electoral Code of the State or his Law of Electoral Justice, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal term to be completed so that they could enter into force in the current electoral process and the governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the deadlines provided in the Law of the Official State Periodic, with the argument that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called the state president's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal", since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
In an interview with the IEM General Council on the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los Angeles Llanderal said that the approval of the relevant guidelines would allow the local electoral body to carry out partial and total counting of votes.
The partial counting of votes in one or more electoral packages may therefore be made on the assumption that: the results of the ballot papers do not match; the ballot papers do not appear in the file of the box or are not held by the chairman of the box; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations in the ballot papers.
In addition, the total count of votes received in all electoral boxes may be made where there is evidence that the difference between the alleged winner of the election in question and the candidate who came second in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition which nominated the second candidate.
The total count of votes may also be made if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the candidate allegedly winning and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case the electoral packages which have been partially counted shall be excluded.
It should be noted that in this situation the election of Morelia is located, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total acts.
