The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put that country on the brink of economic disaster
Italy's appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to present the new government facing a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present the president with the outcome of his talks with political parties in their attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The framework is now well outlined", he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy grapples with a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore the shattered confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry, the market instability put the yield of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to bail out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much".
We believe this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, who was forced to resign on Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a devastating new attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that a failure by Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He'll end his round of meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescuing Italy with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the eurozone's current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections are held.
Monti has said he would like politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist it should be made up of only technicians, an indication of his fears over a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
