Quinteto included the country in its two-decade-long tour
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to perform one of their best shows next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It's been over 20 years of waiting, but the band says it will also make the dream of playing in the country a reality for them.
This was confirmed by bassist and founding member, Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is on the South American leg of its two-decade-long tour of work and on Sunday 20th will be making its only stopover in Central America.
They will perform at the Estadio Nacional, starting at 7:30 p.m., alongside the angeline band The X and the natives of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which is on The Nation on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica, are you aware of what his fans are going through?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once and on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can stay there for a few days.
So we're excited to bring our music there.
I wonder why there's a kind of devotion to the band, fans live intensely the days before.
What do you say to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played in the last 21 years have been in the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that's got us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf, and that's how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they've been delivering huge shows with lots of songs.
What are you planning for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We'll try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we'll try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good, diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the reason for this?
I think it's partly because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we may have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting to us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting to people.
With this tour, they're celebrating 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything they've accomplished?
Yes, I certainly do.
First of all, I don't think either of us imagined we'd be in a big rock band and having done it for over 20 years makes it sound like a dream.
We keep counting our blessings and we're so excited that we can keep making music together.
We all love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to go to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be any better for us.
What did it mean to you to have been a key part of the rise of grunge?
It's always been an honor to be part of that big band group.
We're very close friends of the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's amazing when a movement arises from a group of friends and it's something unusual.
Every now and then, a band from a city comes along, but it's much stranger when five or ten bands come out of the same city at the same time.
We're proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them once in a while.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be friends with all of them still and we're honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came out.
It's also very strange that a band like yours is kept together and with the same members for so long.
Yeah, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is a lot longer than many bands last.
First, I think we're all lucky to be alive and second, we all care about others.
We're all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened up that give everyone freedom to experience.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy, yet thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we've grown, it's been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don't be on tour too much because it's easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for music, that reminds you that you have to respect music and what brought it, without being captivated by being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and we never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration because it lasted so long and most importantly, we're still very close friends of Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think about the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and so much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we're looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing in his mind.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
There's so many of them.
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them I could talk about all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge relevant even though it's no longer a fad?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came out at the same time, and, if there's any relevance now, I think it's something wonderful because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever.
