Fujimori is re-admitted for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength he presents in his legs, his chief medical officer reported.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including tongue cancer for which he has undergone four operations and is under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told TV Channel N that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to get the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He had four operations for tongue cancer, a weight loss of 18 pounds, and other conditions have been added, such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been detained since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Police Special Operations.
In April 2009 he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his rule.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official committee, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and comprised of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican partner, Felipe Calderón, high point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the agenda circulated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propitious for the exchange of information on all political matters between the two nations", the South American Presidency said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderon to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when French president Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country in a list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that prompted Uruguay's rejection and the call for consultation of its ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairman of the G20, a group comprised of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries, since November and has been in force since January this year with the South American country, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the conclusion of tax exchange agreements in order to exit the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), made up of countries that have not implemented all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004 which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The bigot fountainman goes through the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before had he done so in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives this month in stores around the world, has been designed from the start to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld console, which allows you to play in three dimensions without the need for glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how the glasses-free stereoscopy should work", said Nintendo's Spanish spokesman Omar Álvarez during the video game's presentation in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally designed for that support", as until now hits like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesman has argued that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and smooth game.
Alvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "easy" to hook up less skilled users.
Once overcome, the most experienced players will be able to take a "second turn" to the levels of play, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This invasion of Super Mario in three dimensions also means the character's return to a portable console, a fact that had not occurred since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo nods to the fans of the saga and repeats the formula of success of previous installments, consisting that the mustache fountainman will have to travel through mined platforms of dangers with the aim of freeing Princess Peach.
