"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact", he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was performed under visual flight rules, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
Reports at the AICM placed suitable conditions for takeoff, as the aircraft advanced to the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico layers of low-altitude clouds were present.
Routes selected:
It is likely that due to the cloud conditions the crew has been looking for a lower elevation area and greater visibility towards the valley of Cuernavaca.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the aircraft match, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available to date suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and sideways path.
The pattern of dispersion of aircraft debris allows to assume that the helicopter impacted the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the scene of the accident, there is still no evidence of any kind of explosion or fire in the wreckage.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the site.
During fieldwork, aircraft parts have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he was predictably disarticulated along that route.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search of a wider area than the agreed site, around the accident, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, reinforcing the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Security conducts research to discover the gene for obesity in children and young people; it is supported by specialists from the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the gene for obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity' protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Speciality of the National Medical Center Century XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
The team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population, whether or not entitled, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Western Mexico State) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
When celebrating World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he said the aim was to bring together 3,000 children and young people aged between six and 14 years old, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (genetics associated with childhood obesity) were applied to all participants.
Cruz Lopez noted that this research is in response to the concern of healthcare professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys showed that in just six years there was a 77 percent increase in obesity among boys and 47 percent among girls; in terms of overweight, there was also a dramatic increase,' the IMSS specialist noted.
He said the justification for searching for markers is that the country's population differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows detecting whether they are overweight or obese.
He even said there were dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in his neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic changes and even prediabetes.
The information is kept confidential, and doctors give it in writing to parents, who are told about the measures and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the television and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, high fat, protein and high carbohydrate (tams, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) and genetics analysed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would prevent bumps
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a better-performing mixture, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals that the paving sends were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand baches each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of building and maintaining an asphalt paving is the right one, the baches could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
At its conference A technological opinion of the batches, given in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some northern cities, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltene, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that streets in Mexico City are mostly covered with flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that make up the folder, he noted, is bathed in asphalt.
By moving vehicles and generating effort, this allows forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On top of the asphalt, abundant, is placed a final layer called a rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will come into contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
As the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling stock also needs to have the right thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil becomes wet, the water diffuses into the inside of the folder and is difficult to get out, causing all layers of the pavement to soften and thus to form pits.
In the process of forming a batch, he said, the first to wear out is the rolling film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to at the first signals with proper maintenance programs.
The National Investigators' System member explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement should always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to prevent bumps from forming frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair the shells easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
