That was the work of the hammer who identified Alfonso Cano's body.
A lofoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a lofoscopist from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the highest head of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano", through the cotejo of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lofoscopists working in the CTI section, that week was the turn of "disponibility" to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
When he started his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to intern for more than five days in the jungle to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and, after completing the corresponding courses, specialized in lofoscopy, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is, of the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the Alfonso Cano operation, Eliazar was warned to wear minimal clothing for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who was leading the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to carry the decadactilar card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was found, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, which was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local farmer, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplant and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints on the corpse to those on the card.
His eye didn't fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the top head of the FARC.
Searching for the footprint
For a Dactyloscopist from the Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know what we do.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin of error, which can become key to solving crimes.
Apart from identifying corpses, the lofoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When they are caught, many criminals present false IDs or have no papers.
We take their fingerprint and search the database.
The investigator said that in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of a wall from a house, since the thief had held his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not appropriate surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts", he recalled.
The prints can also rule out or reassert suspects in murder cases.
A man was recently found dead, with liquor bottles around him.
The investigation determined that a relative could be a suspect in the crime and, indeed, a print on the bottle matched it.
Although this doesn't guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the crime scene.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that on the objects "the prints are removed with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplant or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians", the CTI expert said.
He made it clear that not everything is as shown on the CSI television show.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a footprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective coupling is made.
