In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they wish to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of a major report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient is asked to do so and has been deemed competent to make the decision.
To begin with, the experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada is in tenth place, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death".
Medicated or not, 77% of Canadians have no access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And even though most Canadians wish to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, Quebec has the highest rate in this regard, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospitals.
As regards the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report came to conclusions that do not match the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide by persons who were not competent or who did not give their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal".
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal", explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians, who favor euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favor of euthanasia, as they believe it would allow people whose death is imminent to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid survey.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not mean that the lives of elderly or disabled people are less valuable.
As for people who have committed assisted suicide, 41 percent of respondents say that no legal action should be taken against them.
The report's authors point out that the situation regarding the maintenance or interruption of patient care is not so clear.
In addition, among their recommendations, they suggest that the penal code should state that withdrawal of health care, if legally refused, is not a criminal offence.
The committee also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses assistance at the end of his life without fear of facing a complaint.
The Committee calls on governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just for cancer.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee calls for it, unless it is used to reduce physical pain, to be considered euthanasia and to be subjected to the same procedures.
