Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada's report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called the position of the experts signing the report "extreme", among other things because euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill patients.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and over 18 can ask for help to commit suicide", says Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to prioritize personal autonomy over any other value in society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health Law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she called a "manifesto in favour of euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who is also a member of the Royal Society of Canada, especially questions the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
