The government of the great Social-Democratic/Christian-Democratic coalition in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include a budgetary "golden rule" in the Constitution to reduce the public deficit and thus prevent a possible degradation of Austria's sovereign credit rating by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social-Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers meeting, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a figure well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
