Energy policy:
The facts must be worth more than dogma
If there is one issue that cannot be addressed by taking short-term considerations into account or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is appropriate that an election meeting be a time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it studies the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are seven billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will mean doubling electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing shortage of fossil resources must be addressed to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a theme that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Germany is therefore alone in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is subject to the need to find a replacement source, nor in Switzerland, which is solely aiming to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few, are moving forward with their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming construction of a power plant that was interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German renewable energy model is sometimes presented as an example, the reality is against such a discourse.
The election of Berlin will mean higher electricity prices, greater energy dependence on increased demand for imported gas, particularly from Russia, and increased CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the damaging effects will be noticeable.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
The wind energy sector is a European champion, with 30% of its electricity coming from it, and it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to wind intermittency.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from Europe's cheapest electricity.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would deprive the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power of realism.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and in fact do not in principle oppose such energy, surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost to building an industrial sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
It is broadly export oriented and encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialising in international markets and capable of creating non-movable jobs.
If France decides to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of €6 billion a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is set to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no evil source.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority which exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, the Three Mile Island, was produced under normal operating conditions; it had no consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the reactor design and some unforgivable human faults.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and cooperation between the safety authorities, and French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While all electricity players who want to build a power plant are studying it, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift to Areva and EDF's competitors, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed "human rights country" status.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see Libération newspaper of May 23) proclaiming in the past that France "needs no foreign talent, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The point is that there is a fair amount of consensus between the left and the right on this issue.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, Michel Rocard set the tone by explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande merely includes trivia, stating that code-development will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electoralally profitable, but economically it's very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent paper summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists about the positive impact of immigration flows on economic growth, wages, and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and hurts employment.
The concerns about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly low-skilled workers, by pushing for their wages to be cut.
But experience shows that immigrants are actually more complementary than substitutes for national workers and mainly occupy jobs in unemployed sectors.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for personnel.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where anesthesiologists are lacking, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in immigration flows means an increase in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, not to mention the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to the average public budget throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the missing growth points "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious but also fragile good.
The European continent should be able to remember this, because although it was invented in Athens over two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of World War II, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have thought that for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know from Napoleon the Little that it was a thoughtful thing.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
