Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas into Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly with Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the opening of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have all rolled the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas will be delivered to Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km pipeline linking the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 and will supply a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third pipe along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land passage through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it will be more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to shut it off from Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has obtained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy sector, given that the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in making its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are large gas consumers and have increasingly limited reserves, a reality.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically", François Fillon confirmed during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom's executives, many in Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine pipe is made of steel coated with cement to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution", says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to step up the measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is uninterrupted throughout its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but the project managers waived it as the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned company to establish itself permanently at sea off their shores.
"If it breaks down, we will stop the gas flow in less than a minute", says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have foreseen joints that are predicted to leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the status of the pipeline shall be ensured by means of an underwater robot, towed by a vessel, which carries out external inspections, as well as by means of a device circulating through the interior of the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repair.
The gas circulation is guaranteed by the pressure alone.
It's 200 bars at the beginning and 100 bars at the exit.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez (9% each) joined the group.
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom subsequently leased to the company, for a renewable period of 25 years, all gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for its full capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported", says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% with bank loans.
The total cost of the two pipes should be EUR 7.4 billion.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of the expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, up to 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit gate.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
In total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back their taste for writing.
It's got an air of adventure, hours of writing by the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took over the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Modo Modo.
And he succeeded.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12,7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the early years, in which only 3,000 booklets were designed, has been left far behind.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts businessmen, students and professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its inception, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre, and has managed to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of e-mails", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and its cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer cases... the brand covers a wide range of supports.
An enviable success: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
Fifteenth Week for Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, compared with 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
"No", says Eric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made in the last 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high as the average, but three times as high.
"However, there is still much to be done".
It is worth mentioning that disabled unemployed persons continue to face numerous obstacles to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years old (on average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed their bachelor's degree and, out of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for disabled people, compared with an average of 38%.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that 'constitute the root of the problem', says Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mindsets are moving forward, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité association noted that the directors surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, with physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from reaching the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set by a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of establishments 'subject to this contribution', as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from EUR 606 million to EUR 480 million).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created a great deal of pressure on companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
Hazard: "A joy"
As they face the Bleus on Tuesday night (20h45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens are not hiding the pleasure they have in this friendly match.
We won't dare say that there was collusion between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side on the podium of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made peace.
Five months after his forward's anger gesture against Turkey, the Belgian national team has nothing but praise for him.
"I was very happy for Eden, for her progress and for being Belgian".
"I want to move forward", replies the forward from Lille.
As for the contrast between his performances in his team and in the selection, "it's a set", has been justified.
"I'm in Lille all year round, which doesn't apply to Belgium.
"I have to get in position".
Called to play against Romania on Friday night, taking into account this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally "glow".
Not forgetting about pleasure.
He's been cheering the Blues since he was seven, as well as during the 1998 and 2000 victorious campaigns.
"I've always been a fan", he says.
This will undoubtedly strengthen the "particular" nature of the meeting.
Especially because he will face "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) ", he recalls.
"We just faced each other recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy".
In simplicity, Leekens has made reference to "pride".
"Pride" for playing "a gala game".
"Pride" also for proving, as "neighbour", that France "is back to being a very high-level team", about a year after Knysna's trauma.
"Laurent Blanc has done a formidable job", he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the technician would be delighted to be able to share a plane with the Bleus to... Brazil, in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are growing", he stressed.
"We're building something; the players are ambitious, they're hungry.
"You'll see him in the next few games". Including the game against France.
Portugal shows great confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal are looking very optimistic about the return match against Bosnia at 22:00 on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the one-off match, both teams lacked realism.
"When these 90 minutes are over, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country".
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
There is no doubt that the Selecçao, which he has led since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Indeed, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there's one game to play and one rival, Bosnia, to defeat.
Given the one-off match (0-0), Friday in the hell of Zenica, it seems obvious that the matter is not decided.
Portugal dominated the game for over an hour, yes, but they couldn't score the valuable goal that would have given them peace of mind.
"It's a good result, but it also carries a risk, since we haven't scored outside the home".
But at home, in the bright Stadium of Light in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced they will pass, in front of an audience that should be equally enthusiastic, even if it is obvious that the match "is very evenly matched", said an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We hope the match is very even, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead", the 42-year-old Portuguese coach said.
"We still have a 50% chance of participating in Euro 2012", said Carlos Queiroz' successor.
Friday's draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
The Bosnians could get a draw, but they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but it also carries a risk, since we haven't scored outside the house", Bento laments.
"We are going to play against a team that has a great technical quality and that has players with a great individual quality", he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting maximum pressure on the Bosnians from the outset to "not give them time to think".
A good idea, as long as, this time, it's realistic.
